  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions worldwide. It typically falls under criminal legislation and is considered a serious financial crime. Key points include:\n\n1. Legal Classification\n- Classified as a criminal offense\n- Violations can result in significant criminal penalties\n- Prosecuted under specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n\n2. Typical Legal Consequences\n- Substantial fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- Criminal record\n\n3. Jurisdictional Scope\n- Most countries have specific laws criminalizing money laundering\n- Often covered under financial crime or criminal code legislation\n- Regulated by national and international legal frameworks\n\n4. International Standards\n- United Nations conventions\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Intergovernmental cooperation in prosecution\n\n5. Common Elements of Criminalization\n- Intentional concealment of illegal funds\n- Transforming unlawful money into seemingly legitimate assets\n- Disguising the origin of criminally obtained funds\n\nMoney laundering is universally recognized as a serious criminal activity with significant legal and financial consequences for perpetrators.",
